This PR fixes how PCB components inside subcircuits are inflated.
It applies the correct transform so all pads, silkscreen, holes, and other PCB elements are placed using component-relative coordinates.

It also adds missing PCB placement fields (layer, X/Y, rotation, do-not-place, obstructs) to resistors, capacitors, inductors, diodes, and transistors.

Tests are updated to match the corrected PCB output.

title: feat: Add differential voltage probe support
description: Adds support for differential voltage probes in simulation, allowing measurement of voltage differences between two points in a circuit. Includes a full-wave bridge rectifier test demonstrating the new functionality.
body:
Adds support for differential voltage probes in simulation, allowing measurement of voltage differences between two points in a circuit. Includes a full-wave bridge rectifier test demonstrating the new functionality.

 Differential Voltage Probe Support
- **Added `referenceTo` prop** to `VoltageProbe` component for specifying reference node in differential measurements
- **Added `color` prop** to allow custom probe colors (optional, defaults to auto-generated color)
- Probes now insert `reference_input_source_port_id` and `reference_input_source_net_id` into circuit JSON when measuring differentially
- Maintains backward compatibility - existing single-ended probes work unchanged
 Dependencies
- Updated `circuit-json-to-spice` to `^0.0.26` to support differential voltage probe rendering in SPICE netlists
 Testing
- **New test**: Full-wave bridge rectifier circuit (`ngspice-spice-analysis04-full-bridge-rectifier.test.tsx`)
  - Demonstrates correct diamond topology for full-wave rectification
  - Uses differential probe to measure voltage across load resistor
  - Validates that output voltage is fully rectified (positive-only)

title: Add error detection flow that validates node module imports progressively
description: Adds a validation flow for node module imports that checks for package declaration in package.json, existence of files in node_modules, unsupported TypeScript entrypoints, and checks for empty dist directories.
body:
## Changes

### New Errors (5 sequential validation steps)

1. **"Node module imported but not in package.json"**
   - Checks if package is declared in dependencies/devDependencies/peerDependencies
   - Thrown early to prevent fallback attempts for undeclared packages

2. **"Node module has no files in the node_modules directory"**
   - Verifies node_modules directory exists with actual files
   - Only enforced when CDN fallback is unavailable

3. **"Node module has a typescript entrypoint that is unsupported"**
   - Detects if main entry points to .ts/.tsx files
   - TypeScript source files require compilation before use

4. **"Node module has no files in dist, did you forget to transpile?"**
   - Verifies dist directory exists when main points to dist/
   - Helpful error for packages with build output in dist

5. **"Package is not declared in package.json"** (jsDelivr fallback)
   - Validates transitive dependencies from jsDelivr don't bypass package.json

### Validation Flow

```
Import Request
    
[STEP 1] Check package.json declaration
     NOT FOUND   Error: "Node module imported but not in package.json"
     FOUND 
[STEP 2] Check node_modules directory
     NO FILES   Error: "Node module has no files in the node_modules directory"
                  (or allow jsDelivr fallback if CDN enabled)
     EXISTS 
[STEP 3] Check main entrypoint
     IS .TS/.TSX   Error: "Node module has a typescript entrypoint that is unsupported"
     IS JS 
[STEP 4] Check dist directory (if main  dist/)
     EMPTY   Error: "Node module has no files in dist, did you forget to transpile?"
     HAS FILES 
 Import module

jsDelivr Fallback Path:
    [STEP 5] Check package.json declaration
     NOT FOUND   Error: "Package is not declared in package.json"
     FOUND   Fetch from CDN
```

title: Add Sub-solvers to fix the gap problem
description: How GapFillSubSolver Works GapFillSubSolver operates as a post-processing cleanup algorithm that creates brand new rectangles to fill empty spaces left after the main RectDiff placement. It follows a four-stage process: 1. SCAN: Detects uncovered areas using grid-based sweep-line algorithm, merging adjacent empty cells into maximal gap rectangles 2. SELECT: Prioritizes gaps by size and multi-layer coverage, choosing the most valuable gap to fill next 3. EXPAND: Places seed point at gap center and grows a rectangle outward until hitting existing rectangles, obstacles, or boundaries 4. PLACE: Adds the successfully expanded rectangle to the solution as a new placement  Fundamental Difference from RectDiff RectDiff solves the routing problem - it places rectangles to enable electrical signal connections based on circuit topology and routing requirements from SimpleRouteJson input. GapFillSubSolver solves the coverage problem - it maximizes board area utilization by filling leftover empty spaces with new rectangles, regardless of routing needs. RectDiff creates rectangles for electrical functionality (routing paths), while GapFillSubSolver creates rectangles for geometric efficiency (space utilization). They serve complementary but entirely different purposes in the placement pipeline: connectivity versus coverage optimization.
body:
## How GapFillSubSolver Works

GapFillSubSolver operates as a post-processing cleanup algorithm that creates **brand new rectangles** to fill empty spaces left after the main RectDiff placement. It follows a four-stage process:

1. **SCAN**: Detects uncovered areas using grid-based sweep-line algorithm, merging adjacent empty cells into maximal gap rectangles
2. **SELECT**: Prioritizes gaps by size and multi-layer coverage, choosing the most valuable gap to fill next
3. **EXPAND**: Places seed point at gap center and grows a rectangle outward until hitting existing rectangles, obstacles, or boundaries
4. **PLACE**: Adds the successfully expanded rectangle to the solution as a new placement

## Fundamental Difference from RectDiff

**RectDiff** solves the **routing problem** - it places rectangles to enable electrical signal connections based on circuit topology and routing requirements from SimpleRouteJson input.

**GapFillSubSolver** solves the **coverage problem** - it maximizes board area utilization by filling leftover empty spaces with new rectangles, regardless of routing needs.

**RectDiff** creates rectangles for **electrical functionality** (routing paths), while **GapFillSubSolver** creates rectangles for **geometric efficiency** (space utilization). They serve complementary but entirely different purposes in the placement pipeline: connectivity versus coverage optimization.

### Switch the `soldermaskCutSetting` to use **Scan mode** with `scanOpt: "individual"`:
- **Scan mode**: Fills shapes by rastering the laser back and forth across the area
- **Cut mode** (previous): Only traces vector outlines
- **scanOpt: "individual"**: Each pad shape is scanned independently to prevent bridging

title: Introduce a new separate laser cut setting for soldermask openings to prevent using copper cut settings
description: Add a new soldermask cut setting with optimized parameters and update relevant handlers to use this setting instead of copper cut settings, ensuring appropriate laser parameters for soldermask layers.
body:
## Changes:
- Add soldermaskCutSetting (index 2) with optimized parameters (1 pass at 150 speed)
- Update all SMT pad handlers (6 files) to use soldermaskCutSetting
- Update all plated hole handlers (7 files) to use soldermaskCutSetting  
- Add preset field support to pcb_board for "soldermask_cutout" mode
- Add includeCopper and includeSoldermask options to conversion function
- Enhance tests to verify correct cut setting usage Cut Settings:
- Index 0 (Cut Copper): 12 passes at 100 speed - for copper traces/pads
- Index 1 (Cut Through Board): 3 passes at 50 speed - for holes/outlines
- Index 2 (Cut Soldermask): 1 pass at 150 speed - for soldermask openings
This ensures soldermask layers are processed with appropriate laser parameters instead of reusing heavy copper cut settings.
